value.value: A common form of dementia caused by multiple cortical or subcortical cerebral infarctions.
The presence of dementia in an individual younger than age sixty five.
Loss of intellectual abilities in an elderly person, interfering with this person's activities.
A degenerative vascular disorder affecting the brain. It is caused by the blockage of the blood supply to the brain. It is manifested with decline of memory and cognitive functions.

label.value: Demyelinating Disorder of Central Nervous System

value.value: Any condition in which there is degeneration of the myelin sheath that covers the nerves of the central nervous system.

A broad group of disorders that affect the myelin sheaths that cover the neurons. Myelin sheathes cover neuronal axons in the central and peripheral nervous system and function to increase travelling impulse speeds. Disruption of this sheath impairs neuronal transmission and can result in disorders such as multiple sclerosis and Guillain-Barre syndrome, among others.
An acute infection caused by Dengue virus. Signs and symptoms include sudden onset of fever, headache, rash, arthralgia, and myalgia. It is transmitted through mosquitoes.
Deficiency in the enamel tissue that results in the formation of grooves, pits, or dents on the surface of the affected teeth.

A syndrome characterized by the presence of a gastrin-secreting tumor, usually in the pancreas or duodenum, resulting in increased gastric acidity and formation of gastric ulcers. Signs and symptoms include abdominal pain and diarrhea. It may be sporadic or a manifestation of multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1.
A disorder that affects the dental pulp tissue.  Examples include inflammation, calcification, and dental pulp exposure.
Depression which is considered strictly biological.
Depression precipitated by events in a person's life.

label.value: Dermatitis due to Food taken Internally

value.value: Dermatitis caused by an allergic reaction to ingested food.

label.value: Dermatophytosis of Groin and Perianal Area

value.value: Dermatophytosis involving the stratum corneum of the skin of the groin and perianal area.
Dermatophytosis involving the stratum corneum of the skin of the scalp and beard area.
A rare syndrome characterized by almost complete absence of body fat, accentuated muscularity, insulin-resistant diabetes, hyperlipidemia, hepatomegaly, and hypermetabolism.

A chronic, pathological complication associated with diabetes mellitus, where retinal damages are incurred due to microaneurysms in the vasculature of the retina, progressively leading to abnormal blood vessel growth, and swelling and leaking of fluid from blood vessels, resulting in vision loss or blindness.
Acute CNS, visual, GI, and cardiac disturbances caused by an overdose of, or intolerance to, the cardiac glycoside, digitalis.
A parasitic infection caused by genus of filarial worms called Dipetalonema. It produces microfilariae in the blood and body fluids.

A Gram-positive bacterial infection caused by Corynebacterium diphtheriae. It usually involves the oral cavity, pharynx, and nasal cavity. Patients develop pseudomembranes in the affected areas and manifest signs and symptoms of an upper respiratory infection. The diphtheria toxin may cause myocarditis, polyneuritis, and other systemic effects.
Infection of the anterior nasal structures by Corynebacterium diphtheriae.
Pseudomembranous colitis resulting from infection by Corynebacterium diphtheriae.

A usually mild form of diphtheria characterized by infection of the skin by corynebacterium diphtheria and the resulting formation of a chronic, shallow ulcer that is sometimes bordered or followed by a bulla.
Infection of the fauces by Corynebacterium diphtheriae.
Infection of the larynx by Corynebacterium diphtheriae.
Infection of the nasopharynx by Corynebacterium diphtheriae.
The pouring forth of a fluid.
Disruption of the normal functioning of the sensory nerves in the skin.

An intracranial or spinal cyst which contains fluid and is composed of arachnoid cells. Intracranial arachnoid cysts may present with headaches, seizures and hydrocephalus. Spinal arachnoid cysts may present with symptoms of radiculopathy.
A pouch or sac-like protrusion in the colonic wall.
Diverticulosis of the colon.

A syndrome characterized by dryness of the cornea and conjunctiva. It is usually caused by a deficiency in tear production. Symptoms include a feeling of burning eyes and a possible foreign body presence in the eye.
Short stature that usually results from genetic mutations. Other causes include hormonal deficiencies and poor nutrition.
Proportionately decreased bodily growth due to failure of the pituitary gland to produce an adequate supply of growth hormone.
A disorder of the skin characterized by loss or reduction of the skin color. It is caused by loss of melanocytes or abnormalities in melanin production.
Colitis resulting from amebic infection.
Abnormally painful abdominal cramps during menstruation.

A rare benign neoplasm arising from the soft tissues of the digits, in young children. It is characterized by the presence of fibroblastic spindle cells, and intracytoplasmic eosinophilic spherical inclusions.
A defect in ossification of bone.
Sudden onset of shortness of breath that causes one to awaken coughing or wheezing; it may be associated with congestive heart failure or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
A chronic mood disorder in which the symptoms are similar to, though milder than, those diagnosed in depression.
A movement disorder characterized by sustained or intermittent muscle contractions, resulting in abnormal movements and/or postures.
Torsion dystonia for which no underlying cause has been identified.
A non-neoplastic lesion that affects the vulva and is characterized by thinning or thickening of the skin and dryness.
Displacement of the lens of the eye secondary to defective zonule formation that is present at the time of birth.
A congenital defect characterized by the absence or hypoplasia of one or more extremities.
An inherited connective tissue disorder characterized by loose and fragile skin and joint hypermobility.
Enlargement of an area of the body due to obstruction within the lymphatic system and the resulting accumulation of lymph.
